@@yThe Crypts of Kel'Shadra@@N

@@eMost who speak of Kel'Shadra speak of bells, vows, and ledgers. They
imagine hooded witnesses in cool chapels writing down final words and
disputed promises. That was the face the order showed cities.@@N

@@dThe Crypts were the other face.@@N

@@yWhen the Bell Synod and Ash Scriptorium discovered that memory custody
could dictate inheritance, absolution, and legal personhood, they required
a place where contested truths could be hidden, remade, or erased. The
Gloamvault processed public doctrine. The Crypts enforced terminal doctrine.
If the Gloamvault answered 'What happened?' then the Crypts answered 'What
version may continue to exist?'@@N

@@eThree deep offices governed the lower strata:@@N

@@d  The Chamber of Redactions @@e- a scrivener office for post-record
  alteration, rewriting names and reclassifying debtors as heretics.@@N

@@d  The Warden Sepulcher Compact @@e- an autonomous martial order whose
  knights were buried where they served and raised through oath-bonding
  rites so command continuity could survive death.@@N

@@d  The Inverse Chancel @@e- a priest-judicial body empowered to declare
  memory 'contaminated,' sealing testimony into bound spirit-hosts.@@N

@@rThe Night of Unsounded Bells was not merely a crisis in the upper vault.
A reform bloc attempted to expose falsified absolutions. When they moved to
publish the books, the Chamber of Redactions triggered emergency doctrinal
authority. Bells were muted. Reliquary units turned inward. Contested ledgers
were shattered into memory shards bound to tormented spirits.@@N

@@yThe shattered gate at the upper approach was broken not by invaders but by
internal actors attempting escape with unaltered records. Those records did
not leave.@@N

@@dThe dead do not rest in the Crypts of Kel'Shadra because annihilation was
recorded there as paperwork, and the paperwork still runs.@@N
